    "# Overview"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this analysis, we aim to determine if there is a relationship between variables of genre, budget, and MPAA ratings, and the international revenue of American blockbuster movies from the years 1977-2019. We used basic plots to do exploratory analysis in order to visually determine if there could be relationships between our variables and outcome. Then we used ANOVA and OLS to determine whether any of the relationships were statistically significant. We found that genre had the most clear influence on the international revenue of a blockbuster film. There is also a positive correlation between film budget and international revenue."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Names\n",
    "\n",
    "- Mizuho Fukuda\n",
    "- Bernardo Lerma\n",
    "- Hung-Tam Yie\n",
    "- Andrew Martinez\n",
    "- Roy Li"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<a id='research_question'></a>\n",
    "# Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Is there a relationship between the international revenue of American movies and factors such as genre, budget, studio, and domestic ratings?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<a id='background'></a>\n",
    "\n",
    "## Background & Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The film industry is a big global player that brings in huge amounts of cash. In 2021 the global box office hit $21.4 billion.[^1] Some blockbusters become cultural icons, reaching across country borders and capturing the imaginations of people from all over the world. The international audience is becoming more and more relevant in Hollywood, as the US market is saturated whereas international markets have plenty of room for growth. There is most notably a huge rise in the Chinese market, going from 1.1% of the global box office revenue to 17.8% in 2015.[^2] \n",
    "\n",
    "One would assume that international success is automatically tied to domestic success, but this is not always the case as many films can perform poorly domestically, but be wildly successful in other regions of the world. For instance, the movie *Ice Age: Continental Drift* made 4 times more international revenue than domestic. Another example would be *Baywatch*, which was not lucrative within the United States, but made up 63% of its box office sales overseas.[^3] One of the most important signs of the necessity of capturing an international audience is that in around 2003, the domestic market became a smaller source of profit for the big six hollywood studios than international markets.<sup>2</sup> \n",
    "\n",
    "All of this means that more than ever, the global reach of a movie is one of the major markers of a movieâ€™s success. Movie producers have been trying different strategies to attain this goal, such as focusing more on visual spectacles than on dialogue heavy movies whose ideas are only relevant to Americans.<sup>2</sup>\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, the international success of a movie could boil down to multiple factors; attaining a strong global reach could be linked to the film's budget, genre, domestic success, etc. where there could be specific factors that are strongly correlated to the success of a movie on a global scale. In our project, we aim to find out the most important factors in creating an international hit.\n",
    "\n",
    "[^1]: Frater, P. (6 January 2022) Global Box Office Hit $21.4 Billion in 2021, Says Analyst. *Variety*. https://variety.com/2022/film/box-office/global-box-office-2021-1235148732/\n",
    "[^2]: \"How important is international box office to Hollywood?\" (15 May 2017). *Stephan Follows*. https://stephenfollows.com/important-international-box-office-hollywood/\n",
    "[^3]: Walters, M. (21 January 2021) American Movies That Other Countries Liked More Than Americans. *The List*. https://www.thelist.com/316805/american-movies-that-other-countries-liked-more-than-americans/"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We predict that the most important factors in determining the international success of a movie are its genre and budget.\n",
    "\n",
    "Out of all genres, we believe that action and adventure films will be the best performers out of them all as they seem to be the most popularized and desired types of films within this modern era. In terms of budgeting, we think that a bigger budget will have a strong positive correlation to a film's international revenue, as they can allocate more resources to production, casting, marketing, etc.\n",
    "\n",
    "Based on this, the films having the greatest international success should be high-budget films within the action and adventure genres."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Dataset(s)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Ideally, we want data on all American movies at least for the past 30 years, including the revenue broken down by domestic and international, title of the movies, genres, air time, location setting, reviews, and other variables that can possibly affect movie sales. We need to find publicly available, accurate and official data. Variables such as reviews and ratings could be different depending on their sources, so we will need to use the same source. The data should be stored in a CSV file or other semi-structured format for ease of analysis. We found our data on Kaggle, and since it is simple information about movies, we don't expect it to be biased in any way.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Dataset Name: Worldwide Blockbusters 2019-1977\n",
    "- Link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/narmelan/top-ten-blockbusters-20191977?select=Blockbusters_2019-1977.csv\n",
    "- Number of observations: 427\n",
    "\n",
    "This dataset includes information about the biggest blockbuster movies of the year, spanning from 1977-2019. Some of the notable columns we are interested in include genre, domestic gross, and worldwide gross. \n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   "source": [
    "We used dtypes to look at the various data types for each column and noticed that columns that store numerical values had data types of strings; we converted these columns values to integers to allow for easier data processing later on. We also checked for null values within our columns and found that they existed within 3 of our columns (mpaa_rating, genre_2, genre_3), in which for our purposes they are acceptable null values. In terms of genres, there exists at least 1 genre for each movie title, so having null values for genre_2 and genre_3 is acceptable for our project. For the mpaa_rating, it is also unnecessary to have a non-null value for each movie title.\n",
    "\n",
    "The data is tidy since it is in a csv format; every row is an observation and every column is a variable. We have also cleaned our dataset by converting the data types and checking for missing values (we still have nulls but they do not affect our analysis)."
   ]

   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "world_block.describe()\n",
    "world_block.dtypes\n",
    "\n",
    "def str_to_int(str_in):\n",
    "    str_in = str_in.replace(',', '')\n",
    "    try:\n",
    "        output = int(str_in)\n",
    "    except:\n",
    "        output = np.nan\n",
    "        \n",
    "    return output\n",
    "\n",
    "world_block['film_budget'] = world_block['film_budget'].apply(str_to_int)\n",
    "world_block['worldwide_gross'] = world_block['worldwide_gross'].apply(str_to_int)\n",
    "world_block['domestic_gross'] = world_block['domestic_gross'].apply(str_to_int)\n",
    "\n",
    "#world_block.isnull().any()\n",
    "#world_block"
   ]

  {

   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

    "world_block.head()\n",
    "#drop rows that have zero international revenue, a.k.a movies that did not air overseas\n",
    "world_block = world_block[world_block.intl_gross != 0]\n",
    "#world_block"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We were looking to find factors that would influence a movie to perform better internationally relative to its domestic revenue. We normalized the international gross by dividing it by the domestic gross and put it into a new column called intl_ratio. This way, we could compare a movie that made 10 million overseas versus a movie that made 100 million overseas."

   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},

   "source": [
    "#add column for ratio of international gross to domestic gross\n",
    "world_block['intl_ratio'] = world_block['intl_gross'] / world_block['domestic_gross']\n",

   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#get rid of outliers in intl_ratio\n",
    "world_block = world_block[world_block.intl_ratio < 5]"

    "#new dataframe of top genres, make a bar plot\n",

   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "In this barplot, we show how the top five genres performed internationally. Although we saw earlier that action is the most popular genre, here we see that adventure and animation actually perform better with international audiences. The top three genres internationally are adventure, animation, and action, which makes sense because these genres are more about the visual spectacle rather than dialogue.    "source": [
    "#perform one-way ANOVA\n",
    "act = world_block[world_block[\"genre_1\"] == 'Action'][\"intl_ratio\"]\n",
    "ani = world_block[world_block[\"genre_1\"] == 'Animation'][\"intl_ratio\"]\n",
    "adv = world_block[world_block[\"genre_1\"] == 'Adventure'][\"intl_ratio\"]\n",
    "dra = world_block[world_block[\"genre_1\"] == 'Drama'][\"intl_ratio\"]\n",
    "com = world_block[world_block[\"genre_1\"] == 'Comedy'][\"intl_ratio\"]\n",
    "world_block_top5_genres = world_block[world_block[\"genre_1\"].isin(['Action', 'Animation', 'Adventure', 'Drama', 'Comedy'])]\n",
    "genre_anova = f_oneway(act, ani, adv, dra, com)\n",
    "print(\"Genre Anova p-value: \", genre_anova.pvalue)"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "An ANOVA is a statistical tool which allows us to see if there is a statistically significant difference between the means of 3 or more independent groups. We ran an ANOVA on 5 groups: Action movies, animation movies, adventure movies, dramas, and comedies.\n",
    "\n",
    "The resulting p-value was 0.001. Using an alpha of 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and tentatively conclude that genre has an influence on how well a movie will do overseas. "
   ]

    "quantile33 = world_block_top5_genres['film_budget'].quantile(0.33)\n",
    "quantile66 = world_block_top5_genres['film_budget'].quantile(0.66)\n",
    "def get_budget_level(budget):\n",
    "    if budget < quantile33:\n",
    "        return 'low'\n",
    "    elif budget < quantile66:\n",
    "        return 'mid'\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        return 'high'\n",
    "world_block_top5_genres['budget_level'] = world_block_top5_genres['film_budget'].apply(get_budget_level)\n",
    "\n",
    "pv = pd.pivot_table(values='intl_ratio', index=['budget_level','genre_1'], data=world_block_top5_genres)\n",
    "pv\n"
   ]

   "source": [
    "To account for the correlation between film budget and genre, we created a pivot table that shows international revenue ration for each genre broken down by film budge. In the process we converted film budget from quantitative data to categorical data with three levels. The pivot table allows us to better see the direct relationship between international revenue ratio and genre without being influenced by a third confounding variable (film budget).\n",
    "\n",
    "We see that there are clear differnces in international revenue ratio between each genre for all three levels of budget, indicating a possible correlation between gnere and international revenue regardless of the effects of film budget."
   ]

    "results = model.fit()\n",

   "source": [
    "We used an OLS Regression model to find the statistical significance of each genre individually. We looked at the 5 main genres, and took into account film_budget as well. This was important as we have determined that there is a difference between the different film genres so we didn't want these differences to confound the analysis. We found that although animation, comedy, and drama did not have a statistically significant impact on the international ratio, adventure did - it had a P value of 0.015. \n",
    "\n",
    "Note: The OLS Regression warned of a multicollinearity error. We determined that this was okay, since the problematic variable was a control variable - film budget. Our variables of interest were not impacted."

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We are using publicly available data on box office numbers for American movies, which we acquired from Kaggle, an open source community-maintained site. There is no personal information in the data, so we are not infringing on the privacy rights of any individuals. Our data only contains information about the movies and their domestic and international revenues. There is no bias in the data because it is simply the objective measured variables of each film included in the dataset. The only potential ethical issue we run into comes from the fact that we are only including American movies, so our analysis does not include movies from other countries around the world."
   ]

    "# Conclusion & Discussion"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In our project, we set out to find the variables which most influenced the success of a film in the international market. We believe we found two.\n",
    "\n",
    "Budget was extremely closely tied to international revenue. Our OLS analysis showed that there was a greater than 99.999% chance that budget was an influential factor.\n",
    "\n",
    "We also looked at genres. This was a bit more complicated, since although an initial ANOVA analysis showed that genre was closely linked to international success, more in depth analysis showed that, on average, different genres had different budgets. Since we knew that budget was so closely related to international success, it was difficult to determine what amount of difference was due to budget, and what amount was due to genre.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, when we controlled for budget in a pivot table and in the OLS, it seemed that there were still differences between genres. The OLS showed that adventure had a statistically significant chance of making more international revenue than all the other genres.\n",
    "\n",
    "Surprisingly, reviewer ratings did not seem to have any effect on a movieâ€™s international revenue.\n",
    "Our findings show that the recipe for a movie which will captivate international audiences is a high budget adventure movie. This makes intuitive sense. A high budget means better production quality and more advertising. Adventure is a genre which focuses on visual spectacle and can speak to worldwide audiences more than genres like comedy and drama which requires more cultural context.\n",
    "\n",
    "In a world where the American film market is saturated, studios will be looking more and more to international audiences for revenue, and we will likely see a larger output of visually stunning action and adventure blockbuster films. "
   ]
